An Act relative to sudden cardiac arrest awareness.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Chapter 111 of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022 Official Edition,
2 is hereby amended by inserting after section 222 the following section:-
3 Section 222A. (a) For the purposes of this section, the following words shall have the
4 following meanings, unless the context clearly indicates otherwise:
5 “Athletic activity”, all of the following:
6 (1) Interscholastic athletics.
7 (2) An athletic contest or competition, other than interscholastic athletics, sponsored by
8 or associated with a school entity, including cheerleading, club-sponsored sports activities and
9 sports activities sponsored by the school or school-affiliated organizations.
1 of 5

10 (3) Noncompetitive cheerleading that is sponsored by or associated with a school entity.
11 (4) Practices, interschool practices and scrimmages for all of the activities listed under
12 paragraphs (1), (2) and (3).
13 “School entity”, all public schools and any school subject to the Massachusetts
14 Interscholastic Athletic Association rules.
15 (b)(1) The department of public health shall work with the department of education to
16 develop and post on its publicly accessible Internet websites guidelines and other relevant
17 materials to inform and educate students about the symptoms and warning signs of heart disease,
18 anatomical and electrical abnormalities of the heart, cardiac distress, and sudden cardiac arrest,
19 including the risks associated with continuing to participate in an athletic activity after
20 experiencing the following symptoms: fainting or seizures during exercise, unexplained
21 shortness of breath, chest pains, dizziness, racing heart rate, extreme fatigue, and any other
22 symptom deemed appropriate by the department of public health.
23 (2) The department shall also provide students the following information annually: a
24 summary of department rules and regulations relative to safety regulations for student's
25 participation in extracurricular athletic activities, including the medical protocol for participation
26 in an extracurricular athletic activity following cardiac symptoms and sudden cardiac arrest;
27 written information related to the recognition of symptoms of heart disease and cardiac
28 abnormalities, as well as sudden cardiac arrest.
29 (3) A student participating in or desiring to participate in an athletic activity and the
30 student’s parent or guardian shall, each school year and prior to participation by the student in an
31 athletic activity, sign and return to the student’s school an acknowledgment of receipt and review
2 of 5

32 of the symptoms and warning sign information sheet developed under this subsection prior to
33 participation.
34 The forms required under this subsection may be in conjunction with any forms required
35 under M.G.L. Ch 111 Section 222, provided that all requirements under both sections are met.
36 (4) A school entity may hold an informational meeting prior to the start of each athletic
37 season for all ages of competitors regarding the symptoms and warning signs of heart disease,
38 cardiac abnormalities, and sudden cardiac arrest. In addition to students, parents, guardians,
39 coaches and other school officials, informational meetings may include physicians, pediatric
40 cardiologists and athletic trainers.
41 (c)(1) In accordance with M.G.L., Chapter 111, Section 222(c), A student who loses
42 consciousness while participating in, or immediately following, an athletic activity, must be
43 removed from participation at that time by the athletic director, coach or athletic trainer.
44 (2) A student who, as determined by a game official, coach from the student’s team,
45 certified athletic trainer, licensed physician or other official designated by the student’s school,
46 exhibits signs or symptoms set forth in this section during an athletic activity, may be removed
47 from participation by said game official, coach from the student’s team, certified athletic trainer,
48 licensed physician or other official designated by the student’s school, if he reasonably believes
49 that said symptoms are cardiac-related. In the absence of one of the persons listed in this
50 subsection, coaches who observe any of the other symptoms set forth in this section, should
51 notify the parent(s) of the student so that the parent(s) can determine what treatment, if any, the
52 student should seek.
3 of 5

53 (3) A student who is removed from play under this provision shall not be permitted return
54 to participation in an athletic activity until the student is evaluated and cleared for return to
55 participation in writing by an appropriate medical professional.
56 (d) The sponsors of youth athletic activities are encouraged to follow the guidance stated
57 in this section.
58 (e) The superintendent of the school district or the director of a school shall maintain
59 complete and accurate records of the district's or school's compliance with the requirements of
60 this section. A school that fails to comply with this section, as determined by the department,
61 shall be subject to penalties as determined by the department.
62 (f) Nothing in this section shall be construed to waive liability or immunity of a school
63 district or its officers or employees. This section shall not create any liability for a course of legal
64 action against a school district, its officers or employees.
65 (g) A person who volunteers to assist with an extracurricular athletic activity shall not be
66 liable for civil damages arising out of any act or omission relating to the requirements of this
67 section, unless such person is willfully or wantonly negligent in his act or omission.
68 (h) The division shall adopt regulations to carry out this section.
69 SECTION 2. The second paragraph of section 1L of chapter 69 of the General Laws, as
70 appearing in the 2022 Official Edition, is hereby amended by adding, in after the word
71 “resuscitation” the following:− and the use of automatic external defibrillators. Instruction in
72 hands only cardiopulmonary resuscitation and the use of automatic external defibrillators must
73 be the most current national evidence−based Emergency Cardiovascular Care guidelines and
4 of 5

74 incorporate psychomotor skills development into the instruction as part of a graduation
75 requirement. “Psychomotor skills” is defined as the use of hands-on practicing and skills testing
76 to support cognitive learning. A licensed teacher shall not be required to be a certified trainer of
77 cardiopulmonary resuscitation, to facilitate, provide or oversee such instruction for non-
78 certification. Courses which result in a certification being earned are required to be taught by an
79 authorized CPR/AED instructor.
80 SECTION 3. Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, the department
81 of elementary and secondary education, based on available appropriations, in Chapter 69,
82 Section 11, will allow as part of the discretionary grant program to provide financial incentives
83 for school districts who require psychomotor skill-based CPR and AED training prior to
84 graduation.
85 (1) Psychomotor Skill-Based hands only CPR Training shall be based on national
86 Guidelines for CPR and ECC which incorporates the use of hands-on practicing.
87 (2) These incentives can be in the form of mini-grants or subsidies to support equipment,
88 professional development for psychomotor skills-based CPR training for students to provide
89 hands only CPR training and use of an automated external defibrillator. There shall be a priority
90 for school districts that are considered high needs as defined as where at least 50% of children
91 are eligible to receive free and reduced priced meals or the school participates in the Community
92 Eligibility Provision or Universal Free Meals or high-need schools may also be defined by Title
93 1 status.
